
\id ECC - Berean Study Bible
\h Ecclesiastes
\toc1 Ecclesiastes
\mt1 Ecclesiastes
\c 1
\s1 Everything Is Futile
\b
\m 
\v 1 These are the words of the Teacher,\f + \fr 1:1 \ft Or the Convener or the Preacher or the leader of the assembly; Hebrew Qoheleth is rendered as the Teacher throughout Ecclesiastes.\f* the son of David, king in Jerusalem: 
\b
\q1 
\v 2 “Futility \f + \fr 1:2 \ft Literally vapor or breath; the Hebrew words translated in Ecclesiastes as forms of futile or fleeting can also be translated as vanity or meaningless.\f* of futilities,” 
\q2 says the Teacher, 
\q1 “futility of futilities! 
\q2 Everything is futile!” 
\b
\q1 
\v 3 What does a man gain from all his labor, 
\q2 at which he toils under the sun? 
\q1 
\v 4 Generations come and generations go, 
\q2 but the earth remains forever. 
\q1 
\v 5 The sun rises and the sun sets; 
\q2 it hurries back to where it rises. 
\q1 
\v 6 The wind blows southward, 
\q2 then turns northward; 
\q1 round and round it swirls, 
\q2 ever returning on its course. 
\q1 
\v 7 All the rivers flow into the sea, 
\q2 yet the sea is never full; 
\q1 to the place from which the streams come, 
\q2 there again they flow. 
\b
\q1 
\v 8 All things are wearisome, 
\q2 more than one can describe; 
